{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527864"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:34:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:34:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14240"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14240"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.1,0.05,0.16,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56123"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6927"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41675"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"449"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17111"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56123"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 86-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her nursing home carer due to increasing tiredness over the last two months. She is a resident in a nursing home. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her regular medications include amlodipine and paracetamol. While she is able to care for herself, she requires a walking frame for mobility and is able to access the community room but not go outside.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 124/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. There is a palpable mass in her right iliac fossa. Investigations reveal a haemoglobin of 82 g/L (119-160). A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Supportive measures alone","Chemoradiotherapy","Defunctioning ileostomy","Stent insertion","Right hemicolectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan has confirmed the diagnosis of a carcinoma of the caecum. In an otherwise fit and healthy individual, the focus would be on active treatment with the aim of resecting the tumour. However, in this case, the patient is elderly, frail, and in nursing home care. Management should be aimed at minimising her symptoms and maintaining her quality of life. Therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Esupportive measures alone\u003C/strong\u003E are the most appropriate plan of management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer tiredness is likely related to her anaemia, which could be alleviated with iron replacement therapy and/or regular blood transfusion as needed. There is no evidence that she has any gastrointestinal symptoms, and the tumour does not appear to be causing any degree of intestinal obstruction. Thus, any direct treatment aimed at the tumour would almost certainly be to her detriment. Linking her in with community based palliative care services would be appropriate and allow for monitoring and management of symptoms outside of a hospital setting. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemoradiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be too aggressive for this frail, elderly patient. The side effects of chemotherapy and radiation could significantly reduce her quality of life without providing substantial benefit given her age and overall health status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ede-functioning ileostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical procedure that diverts the flow of intestinal contents away from a diseased or damaged portion of the bowel. This would be an overly invasive procedure for this patient, especially since there are no signs of obstruction or other acute complications from the tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStent insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used to relieve obstruction in colorectal cancer. However, there is no indication of obstruction in this patient, making this procedure unnecessary and potentially harmful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eright hemicolectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the standard surgical treatment for caecal cancer in fit patients. However, given this patient\u0027s age, frailty, and nursing home residence, the risks of major surgery likely outweigh any potential benefits. The focus should be on maintaining her current quality of life rather than pursuing aggressive treatments that may cause more harm than good.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing elderly patients with advanced cancer, it\u0027s crucial to consider their overall health status, life expectancy, and quality of life. Supportive care, including symptom management and palliative measures, is often the most appropriate approach. In this case, treating the anaemia with iron supplementation and providing other supportive measures as needed would likely provide the best balance of benefit and risk for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Age and general state of health must be taken into account in the management of colorectal malignancy.","Supportive care is often the most appropriate management for frail elderly patients with advanced cancer.","Anaemia in colorectal cancer can often be managed with iron replacement therapy."],"references":["Dotan E, Browner I, Hurria A, et al. Challenges in the Management of Older Patients with Colon Cancer. J Natl Compr Canc Netw. 2012; 10:213\u201325. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3932187/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41675"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14240"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21045"},{"type":"media","id":"21047"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21045"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9WwVJPChmE8ptSkZxmh3MVZekybrQ4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9WwVJPChmE8ptSkZxmh3MVZekybrQ4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":764,"height":457}},{"type":"media","id":"21047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21047"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mhbkDrCB1fAIurw0tKEcU7pS8pW8x0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mhbkDrCB1fAIurw0tKEcU7pS8pW8x0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":742,"height":800}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41675"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T16:46:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T16:47:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6927"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56123"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"se